1500291970																										5889406										http://creativecommons.org/licenses/by-nc/4.0/			2017-04-23T03:11:32Z			https://www.inaturalist.org/observations/5889406					arnel												iNaturalist	Observations	iNaturalist research-grade observations		HumanObservation				https://www.inaturalist.org/observations/5889406	5889406		arnel									wild													"If you look very carefully between all of the striking spikes of Dense-flowered Purple Owl's Clover, you will see what appear to be strange, diminutive heads of oats, with the ""seeds"" all pointing in the wrong way. These actually aren't ""oats"" at all, but a type of plantain whose papery flowers bear some vage resemblance to oat heads. This is the native California Plantain (Plantago erecta), which is also known as the Dwarf Plantain or the Dot-seed Plantain. This patch of Dense-flowered Purple Owl's Clover and California Plantain was photographed in the serpentine grasslands near the junction of the Franciscan Trail and Old Stage Road, at Edgewood County Park.
